"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","before 1020":"před 1020","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, Francie","Pas De Calais, France":"Francie","England":"Anglie","France":"Francie","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Francie"},"da":{"before 1004–1070":"før 1004–1070","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0955–1020":"0955–1020","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0980–1010":"0980–1010","0980–Female":"0980–Afdød","before 1004":"før 1004","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","1019":"1019","1016":"1016","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","before 1020":"før 1020","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, Frankrig","Pas De Calais, France":"Frankrig","England":"England","France":"Frankrig","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Frankrig"},"nl":{"before 1004–1070":"vóór 1004–1070","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0955–1020":"0955–1020","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0980–1010":"0980–1010","0980–Female":"0980–Overleden","before 1004":"vóór 1004","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","1019":"1019","1016":"1016","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","before 1020":"vóór 1020","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Pas De Calais, France":"Frankrijk","England":"England","France":"Frankrijk","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Frankrijk"},"en":{"before 1004–1070":"before 1004–1070","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0955–1020":"0955–1020","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0980–1010":"0980–1010","0980–Female":"0980–Deceased","before 1004":"before 1004","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","1019":"1019","1016":"1016","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","before 1020":"before 1020","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France","Pas De Calais, France":"France","England":"England","France":"France","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dei","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Shanti, Uma, Gayatri, Bimla, Chandra, Kamla, Amala, Aruna, Asha, Darshan, Durga, Indira.","Indian: honorific term used with the names of women, from Sanskrit <i>devī</i> ‘goddess’. It is used as a surname by some women who do not wish to use their traditional name or who do not have a surname as such."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Carnaghi","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Caesar.","Italian: habitational name for someone from Carnago in Varese province, Lombardy. This is a typical Lombardic surname; there surnames derived from placenames usually have a pluralized form."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Giovanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705179,"age":9,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705180,"age":12,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705181,"age":31,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705182,"age":62,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Giovanna Dei Carnaghi was born before 1004, in Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France, her father, Don Michele Carnaghi, was 23 and her mother, Mrs. Don Michele Carnaghi, was 24. She married Roger Corbet in 1019, in Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1070, in England."},"et":{"before 1004–1070":"enne 1004–1070","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0955–1020":"0955–1020","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0980–1010":"0980–1010","0980–Female":"0980–Surnud","before 1004":"enne 1004","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","1019":"1019","1016":"1016","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","before 1020":"enne 1020","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Pas De Calais, France":"Prantsusmaa","England":"England","France":"Prantsusmaa","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"before 1004–1070":"ennen vuotta 1004–1070","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0955–1020":"0955–1020","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0980–1010":"0980–1010","0980–Female":"0980–Kuollut","before 1004":"ennen vuotta 1004","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1020":"1020","1070":"1070","1081":"1081","1019":"1019","1016":"1016","1004":"1004","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","0980":"0980","before 1020":"ennen vuotta 1020","0955":"0955","0988":"0988","Pays de Caux, Upper Normandy, France":"Pays de Caux, Haute-Normandie, Ranska","Pas De Calais, France":"Ranska","England":"England","France":"Ranska","Caux, Allier, Auvergne, France":"Caux, Allier, Auvergne, Ranska"},"fr":{"before 1004–1070":"avant 1004–1070","1004–1070":"1004–1070","0955–1020":"0955–1020","0988–1020":"0988–1020","1020–1081":"1020–1081","0980–1010":"0980–1010","0980–Female":"0980–Décédée","before 1004":"avant 1004","1066":"1066","1010":"1010